# Project 1

## Step 1: Open the `sat_scores.csv` file. Investigate the data, and answer the questions below.
##### 1. What does the data describe?
The data includes all 50 United States, plus Washington DC, and lists the rate of students taking the SAT exam, along with their average Verbal and Math section scores.
##### 2. Does the data look complete? Are there any obvious issues with the observations?

The data is complete, and all values appear to be between 200 and 800 as they should be, however the data needed to be altered in some ways to be most effective. The values for Math, Verbal, and Rate initially appeared as strings, but needed to be changed to integers. It was also important to remove the labels from within the data, as well as the totals from the bottom so they wouldn't effect any of our data.

The data may have been easier to interpret if it had defined "rate" more clearly. Does it refer to all students of a certain age across the country? All graduates? The statistics in general are pretty vague as well, which makes it hard to discern real information. Perhaps the students who aren't taking the SAT are taking the ACT. Perhaps there really are wealth or resource disparities resulting in the vast array of findings.

Ultimately, this data gives us a great deal of information, but still cannot account for the many nuances may have led to their results.
##### 3. Create a data dictionary for the dataset.

State - string - The geographic location from which the data was collected.

Rate - integer - The percentage of students (presumably) who took the SAT.

Math - integer - The average score, out of 800, on the math section of the SAT.

Verbal - integer - The average score, out of 800, on the verbal section of the SAT.

## Step 4: Visualize the data
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline
##### 14. Using MatPlotLib and PyPlot, plot the distribution of the Rate using histograms.

plt.hist(dict2['rate'])

plt.xlabel("Rate")
plt.ylabel('# of States')
plt.title(r'$\mathrm{Histogram\ of\ Rate:}\ \mu=37,\ \sigma=27.28$')
plt.axis([0, 90, 0, 17])
plt.grid(True)
##### 15. Plot the Math distribution

plt.hist(dict2['math'])

plt.xlabel("Math Score")
plt.ylabel('# of States')
plt.title(r'$\mathrm{Histogram\ of\ Math:}\ \mu=531,\ \sigma=35.66$')
plt.axis([420, 625, 0, 14])
plt.grid(True)
##### 16. Plot the Verbal distribution

plt.hist(dict2['verbal'])

plt.xlabel("Verbal Score")
plt.ylabel('# of States')
plt.title(r'$\mathrm{Histogram\ of\ Verbal:}\ \mu=532,\ \sigma=33.03$')
plt.axis([475, 600, 0, 10])
plt.grid(True)
##### 17. What is the typical assumption for data distribution?
The assumption is a normal distribution which would result in a bell-shaped graph.
##### 18. Does that distribution hold true for our data?
It does not hold true for this data.
##### 19. Plot some scatterplots.
plt.scatter(dict2['rate'], dict2['math'])
plt.scatter(dict2['rate'], dict2['verbal'])
plt.scatter(dict2['math'], dict2['verbal'])
##### 20. Are there any interesting relationships to note?

There is a positive linear relationship between math and verbal scores, which is not too surprising. What's interesting to note, however, is the negative correlation between the rate of students taking the SAT and their math and verbal scores. These are predominantly in lower-population states, which most likely indicates only the "smartest" students (or students with the most academic resources) are taking the SAT at all, resulting in a much higher average score than states with higher populations and more students taking the SAT.
##### 21. Create box plots for each variable.

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))

ax1 = fig.add_subplot(131)
plt.boxplot(rate)
ax1.set_title('Box plot for Rate')

ax2 = fig.add_subplot(132)
plt.boxplot(verbal)
ax2.set_ylim([400,650])
ax2.set_title('Box plot for Verbal')

ax3 = fig.add_subplot(133)
plt.boxplot(math)
ax3.set_ylim([400,650])
ax3.set_title('Box plot for Math')
plt.show()
